Continuing. White-bellied Asian ssp. of Barn Swallow. There are two Asian ssp. that reach Alaska: (i) gutturalis which has an incomplete breast band and (ii) rustica which has a solid breast band. Based on distribution, gutturalis is the more expected (in west and southwest AK) with rustica distributed to the north. Photos of this individual suggest a solid, dark breast band suggesting rustica? (The Nearctic form, erythrogaster, breeds in SE Alaska is eliminated due to cinnamon belly.) Observed feeding on the insects attracted to the kelp and seaweed, as well as perched on the ground. Silent.

Media notes: Hirundo rustica observed at a laboratory building at Arctowski Station, King George Island, South Shetlands, on 13 November 2006 (Photo M. Korczak−Abshire)
Observation Details: Here we report a photo−documented record of a barn swallow (Hirundo rustica) from the South Shetland Islands in the Antarctic (south of the Antarctic Convergence Zone). This barn swallow is the first recorded member of the Hirundinidae family on King George Island and is only the second passerine recorded in the South Shetland Islands. More details, see: Korczak-Abshire M., Lees A. C., Jojczyk A., 2011 First documented record of Barn Swallow Hirundo rustica in the Antarctic. Polish Polar Research 32(4): 355-360.

Observation Details: Several over white lake flying low over the water on white lake seen at 11:59am. The numbers kept increasing. I checked the lake in the morning, there was one barn seallow heading to white lake seen from parking lot at 7:12AM. Then we counted 5-10 from the lookout as we walked around white lake. Just before the gathering I estimated the count to be about 20. James and Albert were also at the lake at this time. After the gathering I checked white lake again and this time counted the birds in view picking segments of the lake. Count is a conservative estimate of the number of birds present.

A pair of Barn Swallows are nesting in the pavilion at the end of the boardwalk, a well chosen site were it not for the significant pedestrian traffic. If people are viewing the marsh from the pavilion when the swallows return to the nest after foraging, the birds sometimes wait patiently on the railings on the mid section of the boardwalk. If the pavilion is unoccupied or occupied by appropriately respectful humans, the female typically will return to the nest and the male will perch on a nearby railing and will vocalize. This presumedly allows the male to divert attention from the nest. The two attached photos of the male depict some of those rather diverse vocalizations. The photo of a gaping bill depicts a vocalization that consists of an atonal trill.

Media notes: 0951: female on the Alnus incana snag just N of the diversion.
Observation Details: 1 singing. One or more seen or heard at least 13 times in flight. First seen at 0930, when 1 flew around at ca shrub height at the diversion dam, apparently foraging, then landed in the Alnus incana snag 10 m N of the creek. At 0935 a male and female BHCO flew to the top of the alder snag, at which the BARS took off. At 0944 a BARS was again perched in the alder snag; still there at 0950. Got a video of it preening during this time. Photos suggest it was a female (pale, whitish belly). On the return at 1224 I heard 1 BARS warbling (song portion?) a bit in flight, then calling, and circling over the rocky draw. At 1310 I saw 2 BARS in flight and then perched near the diversion, 1 on a 4 m high dirt pile, the other on a pile of wood N of the stream, ca 40 m farther N. I then saw them for ca 15 seconds in a close chase with twists and turns; heard a variety of upslurred "queet" calls, and then 1 (male) launched into song and then landed on the Alnus incana snag just N of the diversion. I thought the other one was pale underneath like a female, but was not positive.
